1. What is CSS?HTML vs. CSS: HTML acts as the structural skeleton or description of the webpage [01:31]. CSS takes charge of the visual appearance and styling—handling properties like typography, colors, padding, spacing, alignment, and responsiveness [02:04].Cascading: This refers to the browser hierarchy rules applied when an element matches multiple competing CSS declarations. For example, if three different rules try to give a single paragraph different background colors (yellow, red, and blue), CSS relies on specific factors to determine which color takes priority [03:21].2. Three Ways to Add CSS to HTMLThere are three fundamental methods to integrate CSS styles into an HTML document [05:08]:A. Inline CSSStyles are added directly inside individual HTML elements using the style attribute [07:14].Syntax: <p style="background-color: yellow;">Some text</p> [07:19]Pros/Cons: Great for quick fixes, but highly discouraged as a long-term practice. It cluttering the codebase and eliminates code readability as the project scales [09:03].B. Internal CSSStyles are bundled entirely within a single <style> block placed inside the page's <head> container [08:07].Syntax:HTML<head>
  <style>
    h1 { color: green; }
  </style>
</head>
Pros/Cons: Useful for writing styles isolated to a single webpage, but complicates maintenance across multi-page sites.C. External CSS (Industry Standard)Styles are written in a completely isolated file ending with the .css extension, which is then dynamically attached to the HTML using the <link> element [13:01].Syntax (HTML): <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css"> [13:42]Syntax (CSS file): h1 { text-align: center; } [14:23]Pros/Cons: The preferred real-world standard because it maintains a clean Separation of Concerns (keeping HTML structure completely independent of design choices) [19:04].3. Understanding Style Overrides & !importantThe Priority Rule: When a style conflict occurs across methods, Inline CSS beats Internal and External CSS because it sits directly on the target element [11:47].The Override Trigger: If you need an Internal or External style to forcefully win against inline attributes, append !important to your CSS value property [12:14]. This ignores the baseline specificity cascade and overrides all competing instructions [12:25].CSS/* Forces this rule to win universally over inline assignments */
p { background-color: blueviolet !important; } 
4. CSS Selectors in DepthA Selector is a directive that targets specific HTML elements on a webpage so you can apply design configurations to them [19:43].Selector TypeSyntax ExampleBehavioral ActionElement Selectorp { color: brown; }Universal style application. Targets every single match across the entire active viewport document (e.g., matching all <p> tags) [21:02].ID Selector#article1 { background-color: green; }Used to style a single unique element on the page. Uses a hashtag (#) followed by the element's custom id attribute [24:45].Class Selector.para-class { background-color: yellow; }Used to apply identical styles to multiple items on a page. Uses a period (.) followed by the custom class name [26:42].Group Selectorp, article { max-width: 500px; }Used when different tags require the exact same styles. Separate the selectors using commas to avoid duplicating code blocks [29:03].Advanced Targeting Combo: Tag + Class SpecificityYou can chain elements and classes together to be highly selective [30:21]:CSS/* Targets ONLY paragraphs that carry the class name "para-class" */
p.para-class { text-align: center; }
If an <article> tag has the class para-class, it will be completely ignored by the above rule because it is not a <p> element [31:05].